Gordon Paynter wrote:

&gt; Hi all:
&gt;
&gt; Can anyone recommend any tools for visualising or browsing the 
&gt; contents of a set of ARC files returned by a crawl?

&gt;
&gt; Some of our (largely non-technical) librarians are using HTTrack to 
&gt; download sites, and I am testing Heretrix on the same sites. We want 
&gt; to be able to visualise the result of the two crawls, so we can spot 
&gt; the material that HTTrack is missing (on some sites there is a lot of it).

&gt;
&gt; Our preference is to do this in an HTTrack-like format.  For those of 
&gt; you who haven&#39;t used HTTrack, it is not designed for archiving; it is 
&gt; designed as an offline Web site reader.  This means it downloads files 
&gt; from a site(s), and creates a directory tree that loosely replicates 
&gt; the site as static HTML.  All HTML inks are converted to relative 
&gt; links so that the directory tree can be browsed with a web browser and 
&gt; will appear similar to the original site.
&gt;
&gt; It should be fairly straightforward to write a program that reads a 
&gt; set of ARC files, grabs the HTML Pages, tweaks the links, writes them 
&gt; to an HTTrack-like browsable directory tree. Does anyone know if such 
&gt; a program already exists?
&gt;
There isn&#39;t one that we know of.  We&#39;d love to have one.

&gt; Finally, can anyone recommend any tools for browsing or visualising 
&gt; the content of the set of ARC files generated from a single crawl.

Would being able to full-text search and display pages found work?  If 
so, check out nutchwax+wera: 
http://archive-access.sourceforge.net/projects/nutch/.

Otherwise, this link might be of help: 
http://crawler.archive.org/articles/developer_manual.html#arcreader.

